Jamovi - Import data, Data conversion

Problem 1

In this section, you will learn how to read dataset into jamovi.

  1. Go to SPSS TUTORIALS: HOME site. Find the ‘Sample Data Files’ section. Download the following datasets:

    • Data - Comma delimited (*.csv): Sample_Dataset_2014.csv
    • Data - Tab delimited (*.txt): Sample_Dataset_2014.txt
    • Data - Excel format (*.xlsx): Sample_Dataset_2014.xlsx
    • Data - SPSS format (*.sav): Sample_Dataset_2014.sav

    The content of all 4 datasets is the same, they differ only in the format.

  2. Download the Sample_Dataset_2014_Codebook.pdf clicking on ’Data definitions (*.pdf)’. Read this codebook. Use the knowledge of the codebook in the following problems.

  3. Create 4 OMV files based on the 4 different format datasets (CSV, TXT, XLSX, SAV). Use the Hamburger menu / Open / This PC / Browse button to read the files. You will get 4 jamovi windows. Name the files as follows:

    • CSV: dataset_csv.omv
    • TXT: dataset_txt.omv
    • XLSX: dataset_xlsx.omv
    • SAV: dataset_sav.omv

  1. Create a compressed zip file (datasets.zip) from the CSV, TXT, XSLX and SAV versions of the OMV dataset files.

  2. Send the file datasets.zip to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 06 - Problem 1.

Problem 2

In this section, you will learn how to review variables.

  1. From now on, use file dataset_xlsx.omv from Problem 1. Review the variables based on the information in the codebook:

    • add a description to each variable.

    Select the menu Variable and fill the column ‘Description’.

  1. Let’s continue the overview of the variables on the file dataset_xlsx.omv:

    • set the correct measurement type based on codebook.

    Select the button Edit and choose the proper ‘Measure type’. If the variable is nominal, use the ‘Nominal’ item, if it is ordinal, then use ‘Ordinal’, if the variable is an interval or ratio, use the ‘Continues’ item. Use ‘ID’ if the variable identifies a row. Date and time are not handled by jamovi, so they should be set Nominal or Ordinal.

  1. Let’s continue the overview of the variables on the file dataset_xlsx.omv:

    • if necessary, rename the levels of the categorical variables.

    After reviewing the codebook and the database, it is worth renaming the levels of the following categorical variables:

    • Rank

      • 1 = Freshman
      • 2 = Sophomore
      • 3 = Junior
      • 4 = Senior

    • Gender

      • 0 = Male
      • 1 = Female

    • Athlete

      • 0 = Non-athlete
      • 1 = Athlete

    • Smoker

      • 0 = Nonsmoker
      • 1 = Past smoker
      • 2 = Current smoker

    • LiveOnCampus

      • 0 = Off-campus
      • 1 = On-campus

    • HowCommute

      • 1 = Walk
      • 2 = Bike
      • 3 = Car
      • 4 = Public transit
      • 5 = Other

In the case of most variables, based on the codebook, the numerical values are simply transferred to the text version. This is an important step because meaningful level names make analysis easier (see Rank variable.). In the case of ordinal variables, the descending order of the levels is ensured with the help of the up and down arrows. In our case, there was no need to change the order of the levels.

Note that all the level names in the codebook are also among the level names of the categorical variable. Even when such a level name does not occur in the current database. Such is the HowCommute variable in our case, when we had to enter the value ‘5=Others’. In such a case, do not forget to turn on the Retain unused levels in analyses switch.

  1. Send the file dataset_xlsx.omv to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 06 - Problem 2.

Problem 3

In this section, you will practice jamovi data conversion.

  1. Download the star ‘Student Teacher Achievement Ratio (STAR) project data’ from this site.

  2. Open the dataset in jamovi and save as star.omv.

  3. Review the dataset variables based on star’s DOC link:

    • have meaningful variable names
    • have a description
    • all variables must be in the correct measurement type
    • categorical variables should have all levels (used and unused)
    • all level names should be meaningful
    • in the case of ordinal variables, the levels should be in the correct order.

  4. Send your star.omv to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 06 - Problem 3.

Problem 4

In this section you will learn how to extend jamovi with new capabilities.

  1. Jamovi’s knowledge can be expanded with modules. Install the following modules and take before and after pictures to show how the modules will look in jamovi:

    • moretests
    • ztestvis
    • lsj-data
    • r-datasets

    Each installed module should therefore have 2 images.

  1. Summarize the installation of the 4 modules above and the total of 8 screenshots in a new RStudio project, a Quarto document. Create an HTML file named modules.html.

  2. Send your modules.html to the abari.kurzus@gmail.com. The subject of this email is Lab 06 - Problem 4.
